            , and the Tankard was left me by my Uncle 
               <persName id="t17251013-44-person278">
                  Edward 
                  Barry 
               <interp inst="t17251013-44-person278" type="surname" value="Barry"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t17251013-44-person278" type="given" value="Edward"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t17251013-44-person278" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            , who is lately dead in Ireland, and these two Letters E and B stand for his Name. Not thinking this Account satisfactory, I had him before the Mayor, who committed him to the Town Prison; and upon my publishing an Advertisement, Mrs. Barwell came down. When she saw the Prisoner, she asked him if he knew her? And he answer'd, Yes, Madam, to my Shame, - my Life is in your Hands.</p>
               <p>The Prisoner thus made his Defence: I had the Tankard it's true; but I know no more how I came by it than the Man in the Moon; for I was drunk over Night, and next Morning I found myself asleep in S. James's Park, with the Tankard in my Pocket. <rs id="t17251013-44-verdict216" type="verdictDescription">
                     <interp inst="t17251013-44-verdict216" type="verdictCategory" value="guilty"></interp>
               Guilty
            </rs>. <rs id="t17251013-44-punish217" type="punishmentDescription">
